post_text: GMR elementary teachers were pleasantly surprised on Monday morning when Deb Korczak and Judy Pulczinski from the Greenbush Area Friends of the Library presented each of their classrooms with a check for $900. These checks will be deposited in each classroom's Scholastic book account and all GMR elementary students will be able to order "free" books through the upcoming school year! The Friends of the Library group feels strongly about the importance of "putting books into the hands of children". Thank you to this wonderful, generous group for promoting literacy in our communities! üìöüêä

***UPDATE*** The Minnesota State High School League is allowing a one year exemption for the physical requirement if an athlete had one in the past. For example, if you had a physical in 7th grade and are entering 10th grade, you do not need one this year. If you have never had a sports physical, you still need one.

Reminder to GATOR ATHLETES! Sports Physicals are good for 3 years so typically needed in 7th and 10th grades. The MSHSL form is linked at the GMR website and below.

post_text:
The Greenbush Middle River School District will start the 2020-2021 school year with in-person learning for Pre-K-12 students with safety precautions for students and staff (this includes masking requirement as per Governor Walz Executive Order on July 22, 2020).

On Thursday, July 30, Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz announced the State‚Äôs plan for reopening the state‚Äôs K-12 public schools. The Plan has a focus on localized decision-making driven by the spread of COVID-19 data. The plan is based on the number of COVID-19 cases in a county for how schools may move between in-person, hybrid and distance learning models in response to the spread of the virus in their communities throughout the school year.

Because of the current [low] prevalence of COVID-19 within the boundaries of the GMR District (as of July 31, 2020), the GMR School intends to expand the planning process to begin the school year with in-person learning. More specifics for GMR‚Äôs Back-to-School plans to follow.

***Get help buying food while schools are closed***

If your family participated in the free or reduced school lunch program during the school year, there is a new program that can help provide your family with a food benefit over the summer. Please take a moment to look at and apply for P-EBT: www.mn.p-ebt.org.

This program is designed to help families with food costs during the COVID 19 pandemic. Families with SNAP or MFIP benefits will automatically receive benefits with the new program. Families utilizing school based Free or Reduced Lunch programs, can also apply.

LifeCare Medical Center is offering BLAST babysitting training on Monday, March 16th from 12:30-4:30 p.m. at the GMR School Cafeteria (early out day).

Cost is $20, please register at https://lifecaremedicalcenter.org/babysitter-education/ OR call Paula @ 463-4301. The BLAST! course is designed for potential babysitters ages 11-14. This comprehensive training program can prepare children to interview for a babysitting job, select safe and suitable games and activities, prevent accidents, perform first aid, and begin babysitting safely and competently. Each participant will receive a certificate of completion, course materials, babysitting bag, and a mini first aid kit.

The GMR Kindergarten class was EXCITED & PROUD to donate over 100 cleaned mascara wands to the Appalachian Wildlife Refuge campaign: Wands for Wildlife

This is a nonprofit wildlife rehabilitation in western North Carolina that recycles old mascara wands to help her move fly eggs and larva from the fur of animals. They work great because the bristles are so close together and gentle to use on the injured and orphaned wild animals receiving care.

post_text:
Greenbush-Middle River Elementary students will be collecting money for Jump Rope For Heart November 18th - December 2nd. All money raised goes to the American Heart Association to help fund community initiatives, education, research and quality of care - all to fight the number one killer in the world, heart disease.

The students can win prizes and also earn a US Games gift certificate, depending on the amount collected, which can be used for physical education equipment for the GMR School. If you are not contacted by a student, but would still like to donate to this worthy cause, you can bring a check (made out to the American Heart Association), the office at the GMR School.

Thanks for your support!

post_text: The Science Museum of Minnesota, in conjunction with OtterTail Power Company, presented to GMR 4th and 5th graders today about different types of energy. The students participated in activities while learning about wind, coal, solar, and nuclear energy. There was also discussion about renewable and non renewable energy and the byproducts, such as pollution, of each type.

post_text: Grades 4 and 5 had special guests visit today. Russell Wicklund, a Greenbush High School alum, and his son Russell shared their story about hiking the entire Appalachian Trail earlier this year. Last year‚Äôs 4th graders followed along with them via their Facebook page. The 2200 mile journey took the father/son duo about 6 months, starting in Georgia and ending in Maine. Thanks for sharing your story with us!

post_text: There will be a test of the GMR Emergency Communication System on Tuesday, November 5 at about 5:00 pm. It is only a test. If you are a GMR parent who doesn't receive the test message on Tuesday, Nov. 5th, you can call the Principal's Office to get your name on the call list. If you are a GMR parent who no longer has children in school, you can call the Principal's Office to remove your name from the call list. Thank you!
